# JAVASCRIPT OPERATORS
JavaScript operators are special symbols used to run calculations, compare values, and assign data to variables. Think of them as the mathematical verbs of your code.
JavaScript features 11 primary categories of operators grouped by the specific functions they execute.
# TYPES OF OPERATORS
1. Arithmetic Operators
Operator     Uses                            Syntax
+	           Addition                        console.log(10 + 5); // Outputs: 15
-	           Subtraction                     console.log(10 - 5); // Outputs: 5 
*	           Multiplication                  console.log(10 * 5); // Outputs: 50
**	         Exponentiation                  console.log(2 ** 3); // Outputs: 8
/	           Division                        console.log(10 / 5); // Outputs: 2
%	           Modulus (Division Remainder)    console.log(10 % 3); // Outputs: 1
++	         Increment                       let x = 5; console.log(++x); // Outputs: 6
--	         Decrement                       let x = 5; console.log(--x); // Outputs: 4
There are two types of increment and decrement operators in JavaScript: Pre-increment/Pre-decrement and Post-increment/Post-decrement.
1) Pre-Increment (++x)
The value is increased before it is used.    let x = 5; console.log(++x); // 6
2) Post-Increment (x++)
The value is used first, then increased.     let x = 5; console.log(x++); // 5
3) Pre-Decrement (--x)
The value is decreased before it is used.    let x = 5; console.log(--x); // 4
4) Post-Decrement (x--)
The value is used first, then decreased.     let x = 5; console.log(x--); // 5
# Easy Way To Use
Pre (++x, --x) → Change first, then use.
Post (x++, x--) → Use first, then change.

